The paper deals with the parameterized complexity of a graph problem, specifically the ${\cal F}$-M-Deletion problem, where ${\cal F}$ is a fixed collection of graphs. The parameter is the treewidth of the input graph, which is a fundamental concept in graph theory and algorithms. The paper also mentions planar graphs and graphs embedded in surfaces, which are topics commonly studied in computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper uses techniques from graph theory, combinatorics, and complexity theory, which are relevant to several sub-categories such as cs.DS, cs.GT, and cs.CC. Finally, the paper provides lower bounds based on the Exponential Time Hypothesis (ETH), which is a topic in computational complexity and hardness of approximation (cs.DM).
